<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8" ?>
<!--
SPDX-License-Identifier: MulanPSL-2.0

FastRTPS profile that disables the SHM transport.

Why: with host networking and host IPC, the sim and mapping containers
share /dev/shm. But FastRTPS's SHM transport uses port-hash-named shm
files locked by the writer participant's GUID; cross-container data
transfer through those locks does not work reliably (discovery goes
through fine over UDP, but `topic echo` / `topic hz` time out even
though both endpoints see each other).

Forcing UDPv4-only for both sides removes the SHM path entirely;
FastRTPS still uses UDP unicast for data delivery, which is fast enough
on loopback / host-net and avoids the SHM-namespace mess.

Do NOT pin this to the loopback interface (interfaceWhiteList /
metatraffic localhost): the sim announces its topic locators on the
host's primary interface, so a loopback-only nav2 participant stops
discovering /odom and /scan. Keep the transport on all interfaces.

Note on bringup reliability: with many DDS participants on the shared
host network, the default net.core.rmem_max (208 KB) can overflow under
the endpoint-discovery burst and drop nav2's lifecycle change_state
replies, stalling bringup. The robust fix is to raise the host's UDP
buffers (see the README "DDS / sysctl tuning" note); this profile keeps
the transport simple and portable.

Apply via FASTRTPS_DEFAULT_PROFILES_FILE pointing to this file.
-->
<profiles xmlns="http://www.eprosima.com/XMLSchemas/fastRTPS_Profiles">
  <transport_descriptors>
    <transport_descriptor>
      <transport_id>udp_only</transport_id>
      <type>UDPv4</type>
      <!-- Ask for large socket buffers. The OS caps these at rmem_max, so
           this only helps where rmem_max is tuned; harmless otherwise. -->
      <sendBufferSize>4194304</sendBufferSize>
      <receiveBufferSize>4194304</receiveBufferSize>
    </transport_descriptor>
  </transport_descriptors>

  <participant profile_name="participant_no_shm" is_default_profile="true">
    <rtps>
      <userTransports>
        <transport_id>udp_only</transport_id>
      </userTransports>
      <useBuiltinTransports>false</useBuiltinTransports>
    </rtps>
  </participant>
</profiles>
